Examining Police Misconduct - Evidence from Chicago

Sebastian Montenegro

August 5, 2020

I will study data from the Citizens Police Data Project which can be accessed via their website. The datasets can be downloaded at different grouping levels such as police districts, wards, beat, and neighborhoods. The data are presented in comma-separated value files that contain different variables describing the characteristics of the interaction between the police officer and the complaining witness.

You can access the data and code that I used to clean the data files by clicking on the links.

I will start by providing you with a couple of visualizations that are very interesting in order to understand what’s going on within the Chicago PD.

We will need the following packages:

devtools::source_url("https://github.com/sebmontenegro/functions/blob/master/preload.R?raw=TRUE")

Allegations over time

This is how the number of allegations vary overtime for the Chicago PD

allegations %>%
  filter(IncidentDate>=as.Date("1999-01-01")) %>%
  count(Date = factor(IncidentDate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.Date(Date),y=n))+
  geom_line(color="skyblue4")+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(x ="", y = "Number of Allegations")

It has a downward trend and has a drop in 2005 and 2016.

Most frequent allegation categories

This next plot presents the most frequent allegation category by finding.

allegations %>%
  filter(Finding!="Unknown") %>%
  count(Category = Category, Finding = Finding) %>%
  filter(n>=15) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Category,-n),y=n,fill=Finding))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(x ="Allegation Category", y = "Number of Allegations")+coord_flip()+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  guides(fill=guide_legend(nrow=2,byrow=TRUE))+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0),legend.position = "bottom")

The most frequent category is Operation/Personnel Violations. However, those allegations may be sustained, not sustained, unfounded, exonerated, or the allegation might be filed with no affidavit.

Note that Excessive Force with Injury is the most frequent allegation in the records, but none of the allegations is sustained. Also note that sustained allegations disproportionately less frequent.

Final outcome and finding

Now, let’s explore final outcome for allegations recorded in the data. The outcome-axis is order in frequency, so that No Action Taken is the most frequent.

allegations %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           Finding!="Unknown") %>%
  count(Outcome = factor(Outcome),Finding = factor(Finding))%>%
  group_by(Outcome) %>%
  mutate(pct = prop.table(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(Outcome,level=levels(forcats::fct_infreq(allegations$Outcome))),y=pct,fill=Finding))+
  geom_bar(position = "fill", stat = "identity",color='black',width=0.9) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(pct*100,0),"%")),position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 2)+
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  labs(x ="Outcome", y = "Percentage of Allegations")+ coord_flip()+
  theme(legend.position="bottom") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0))

The vast majority of allegations that end up in some sort of corrective action are Sustained. Note that for those that wind up with No Action Taken, zero percent are Not Sustained.

Race interaction and finding

Something striking can be taken from this picture: The percentage of Sustained allegations filed by Black witnesses varies from 2% to 3% and is dramatically lower than that for White witnesses, which varies from 18% to 39%.

Random Forest Model

Now, I am going to grow a random forest model in order to predict whether an allegation is going to end up in a sustained finding or not.

The first that I will do is to split the sample into two groups: the training set and the validation set. I will utilize the training set to grow the model and the validation set to determine the accuracy of the model.

set.seed(100)
train <- sample(nrow(data.rf), 0.7*nrow(data.rf), replace = FALSE)
TrainSet <- data.rf[train,]
ValidSet <- data.rf[-train,]

No, look at the distribution of the outcomes. There are too many observations for not sustained or different van those forces teamed allegations. Therefore, I am going to balance the training sample.

table(TrainSet$Finding)
## 
## Other Than Sustained            Sustained 
##                53629                 4724

To balance the training sample, I am going to randomly draw the observations from each category.

#Balance Train set
cat <- as.character(data.frame(table(TrainSet$Finding))$Var1)
num <- min(data.frame(table(TrainSet$Finding))$Freq)

tmp <- NULL
for(i in 1:length(cat)){
  a <- TrainSet[which(TrainSet$Finding==cat[i]),]
  a <- a[sample(nrow(a),num, replace = FALSE),]
  tmp <- rbind(tmp,a)
}
TrainSet <- tmp
rm(tmp,a,cat,num,i)

Now we are good to proceed to grow the random forest. In this case I’m going to contact a classification exercise rather than a regression.

model1 <- randomForest(Finding ~ . -Outcome, data = TrainSet, importance = TRUE, proximity = TRUE, do.trace = 100)

Normally what I would do with this type of models is to fine-tuning the parameters of the model. The two parameters to tune in the random forests are the number of trees grown (ntree) and the number of variables randomly sampled as candidates at each split (mtry). I will not present here all the different options that I tried. I will just stick to this model which seemed to be the best one. Note that the out-of-the-bag (OOB) error rate in this model is about 20%, which is not the best for a model of this kind. These means that the model is wrong 20% of the times that the it is evaluated in an out-of-the-bag sample.

Now, let’s see how the model behaves when predicting using the validation sample

resultdt <- predict(model1, newdata = ValidSet, type = "class")

# Confusion matrix
cm <- table(ValidSet$Finding, resultdt, dnn = c("Actual", "Predicted"))
cm
##                       Predicted
## Actual                 Other Than Sustained Sustained
##   Other Than Sustained                17609      5298
##   Sustained                             327      1775
accuracydt <- sum(diag(cm)) / sum(cm)
accuracydt
## [1] 0.775081

This model is able to correctly identify 77% of the cases evaluated in the validation set.

Now, let’s look at the importance of the variables that were included in the classification random forest.

varImpPlot(model1)

It looks like allegation type and allegation category are the two most important variables to predict whether a result of an investigation is going to be sustained or not.
